ðŸ“˜ Day 21 â€“ Git Interactive Rebase (Repo Summary)
ðŸ”¹ Topic: Interactive Rebase (git rebase -i)

Interactive rebase is a powerful Git feature that allows you to rewrite and clean commit history in a controlled and intentional way. It helps transform a messy or noisy commit log into a clear, logical, and linear history before merging code.

Using interactive rebase, you can:

Fix commit message typos

Combine related commits

Reorder commits logically

Remove unnecessary or wrong commits

ðŸ”¹ Starting an Interactive Rebase

To edit recent commits, interactive rebase is started using:

git rebase -i HEAD~N


Example:

git rebase -i HEAD~7


This opens the last 7 commits in an editor and allows you to decide what to do with each commit.

ðŸ”¹ Common Interactive Rebase Commands (Used Inside Editor)
pick    â†’ keep commit as-is
reword  â†’ change commit message
edit    â†’ modify commit content
squash  â†’ combine commit with previous one (keep messages)
fixup   â†’ combine commit and discard message
drop    â†’ delete commit completely

ðŸ”¹ Fixing a Commit Message (Reword)

To correct a typo in a recent commit message:
git rebase -i HEAD~2


Change:

pick <commit-hash>


to:

reword <commit-hash>


This updates the commit message and rewrites the commit hash.

ðŸ”¹ Combining Commits (Squash / Fixup)

To combine multiple related commits into one:

git rebase -i HEAD~4


Change the second commit to:

squash <commit-hash>


or:

fixup <commit-hash>


This creates a single, clean commit for related changes.

ðŸ”¹ Removing Unwanted Commits (Drop)

To remove an unnecessary commit from history:

git rebase -i HEAD~1


Change:

pick <commit-hash>


to:

drop <commit-hash>


This removes the commit and its changes completely.

ðŸ”¹ Handling Conflicts During Rebase

If conflicts occur:

git add <file>
git rebase --continue


To cancel rebase completely:

git rebase --abort

ðŸ”¹ Visualizing Commit History

To clearly understand how rebase changes history:

git log --all --graph --oneline --decorate

ðŸ”¹ Key Takeaway

Interactive rebase is best used before pushing code or on feature branches. It helps maintain a clean, readable history but should be avoided on shared or already-pushed branches.